{"questionId":"22205","questionHtml":"<p>Find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> where the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> has points of inflexion. Justify your&nbsp;answer.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Special note:</strong> In this question if candidates use the word 'gradient' in&nbsp;their reasoning. e.g. gradient is positive, it must be clear whether this&nbsp;is the gradient of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> or the gradient of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo></math> to earn the <em><strong>R</strong></em> mark.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math>&nbsp;has points of inflexion when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>A2</em></strong></p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;has turning points at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p>\n<p>OR</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>''</mo><mfenced><mi>q</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>''</mo><mfenced><mi>r</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>''</mo><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;changes from increasing to&nbsp;decreasing or vice versa at each of these <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-values (may be seen in a sign&nbsp;diagram clearly labelled as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>''</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>R1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>Award <em><strong>A0</strong></em> if any incorrect answers are given. Do not award<em><strong>&nbsp;A0R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3</strong></em><em><strong>&nbsp;marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22205","referenceCode":"21N.1.SL.TZ0.9c.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the values of x where the graph of f has points of inflexion. Justify your answer.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.2—Increasing and decreasing functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.11—Definite integrals, areas under curve onto x-axis and areas between curves"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}